    "discriminators": [
     "The one WIND subcategory DSP owns outright, and it is a clean physical story: a howl, or wind singing in wires, is an AEOLIAN TONE — vortex shedding locks onto a resonance and the noise band grows a pitch. So harmonicity lifts off the floor (gated >= 0.30, expected ~0.62) and spectral_flatness collapses to ~0.22, while every other wind sits at 0.5 or above and is gated OUT at harmonicity 0.60. The two gates are complementary; the pair is genuinely non-overlapping.",
     "The tone WANDERS (spectral_centroid_deviation_hz stays high) and is often inharmonic — an edge tone, not a played note — which is what separates it from a horn, a drone or a motor whine.",
     "WIND-INTERIOR often carries a mild moan; the boundary is harmonicity, and UCS's own text routes the overtly tonal cases here."
    ],
